5":"1092–1155","1036–1096":"1036–1096","1045–1135":"1045–1135","about 1096":"circa 1096","1136":"1136","1135":"1135","1036":"1036","1112":"1112","1045":"1045","1155":"1155","1076":"1076","1086":"1086","1096":"1096","1070":"1070","1092":"1092","Skipton, Yorkshire, England":"Skipton, Yorkshire, England","Normandie, France":"Normandie, Frankrijk","Basset, Lot-Et-Garonne, Aquitaine, France":"Basset, Lot-et-Garonne, Aquitaine, Frankrijk","Manche, Normandy, France":"Manche, Normandie, Frankrijk"},"en":{"1070–1096":"1070–1096","1076–1155":"1076–1155","1070–1136":"1070–1136","1092–1112":"1092–1112","1092–1155":"1092–1155","1036–1096":"1036–1096","1045–1135":"1045–1135","about 1096":"about 1096","1136":"1136","1135":"1135","1036":"1036","1112":"1112","1045":"1045","1155":"1155","1076":"1076","1086":"1086","1096":"1096","1070":"1070","1092":"1092","Skipton, Yorkshire, England":"Skipton, Yorkshire, England","Normandie, France":"Normandy, France","Basset, Lot-Et-Garonne, Aquitaine, France":"Basset, Lot-et-Garonne, Aquitaine, France","Manche, Normandy, France":"Manche, Normandy, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Rumilly","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["1  Norman, English: locative name from Romilly in Eure (France). Some examples may belong under (2) or (3), and there has probably been confusion between them.","2  Norman, English: locative name from Remilly in Manche (France).","3  English: locative name from Romiley (Cheshire)"],"variants":[{"name":"Rumley","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): habitational name from Romilly in Eure (France) or from Remilly in Manche (France).","English: habitational name from Romiley (Cheshire), from Old English <i>rūm</i> ‘roomy, spacious’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’.","Altered form of Swiss German <b>Rümmeli</b> or <b>Rümmele</b>, variants of   Rummel  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705183,"age":16,"year":"1086","julianDay":2117714,"title":"Domesday Book","description":"Domesday Book is Britain's earliest extant public record with information containing land surveys and landholdings commissioned by William I. The book was completed in 1086.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/domesday/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Dom